# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biodiversity-action-plan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The **Biodiversity Indicators Partnership** (BIP) brings together a host of international organizations working on indicator development, to provide the best available information on biodiversity trends to the global community.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership was initially established to help monitor progress towards the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) 2010 Biodiversity target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] However, since its establishment in 2006 the BIP has developed a strong identity not only within the CBD but with other Multilateral Environmental Agreements (MEAs), national and regional governments and other sectors.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] As a result, the Partnership will continue through international collaboration and cooperation to provide biodiversity indicator information and trends into the future.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Central to the renewed Partnership will be its revitalized relationship with the Convention on Biological Diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In 2010, at the 10th Conference of the Parties to the CBD held in Nagoya, Japan the BIP was referenced eight times in the official adopted decisions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] These references demonstrated a clear will for the Partnership to continue supporting the CBD with implementation of the Strategic Plan for Biodiversity 2011–2020.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Strategic Plan consists of 20 new biodiversity targets for 2020, termed the ‘Aichi Biodiversity Targets’.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Biodiversity encompasses the entire variety of life on Earth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] It is vital for human survival and is a key measure of the health of our planet.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Human activities are irreversibly impacting biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In all regions of the world species extinction rates have increased, ecosystems have been degraded, and genetic diversity has declined.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] An essential part of reaching the 2010 biodiversity target was being able to measure and communicate progress.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] For this purpose the CBD adopted a framework in 2004, which included the use of a range of biodiversity indicators to measure progress towards the 2010 target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In 2006 this framework was further elaborated and the '*2010 Biodiversity Indicators Partnership* was established, as a global initiative to further develop and promote indicators for the consistent monitoring and assessment of biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The 2010 BIP was established with major support from the Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The main objective of the Partnership is a reduction in the rate of biodiversity loss at the global level, through improved decisions for the conservation of global biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] To establish links between biodiversity initiatives at the national and regional levels to enable capacity building and improve the delivery of the biodiversity indicators.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Through CBD governance and advisory bodies, the global biodiversity community identified a suite of 17 headline indicators from the seven focal areas for assessing progress towards, and communicating the 2010 target at a global level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Since 2007, partners have worked to ensure the most accurate information is available to decision makers.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP indicators have substantially contributed to the 3rd edition of the *Global Biodiversity Outlook*, featuring in the *Status and Trends in Biodiversity* chapter of this flagship CBD publication.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership also works to integrate indicator results into coherent, compelling storylines giving a more understandable picture of the status of biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The Partnership brings together a host of international organisations working to support the regular delivery of biodiversity indicators at the global, national and regional levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP works to communicate links between the partnership’s work and all potential users, including highlighting the utility of the components of the CBD indicator suite for other multilateral environmental agreements.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Engagement with the private sector is also an objective for the partnership.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] The BIP has provided financial support and currently provides ongoing technical support to the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI), to advance the integration of related indicators into corporate performance measures.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] In addition to improving global-scale indicators, the BIP has been actively involved in supporting national and regional initiatives; facilitating indicator development and implementation that responds to country-specific national biodiversity priorities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] A programme of capacity building workshops has been run across the globe, bringing together the various institutional representatives involved in national indicator development to share experiences and best-practice.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] Some 45 countries have been engaged to date.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] A series of guidance documents on national indicator development have been published, together with a web portal (www.bipnational.net).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-indicators-partnership] This multi-language website is the most comprehensive online resource of guidance, support and shared experiences of effective indicator development for countries and regions looking to develop biodiversity indicators.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] The **2010 Biodiversity Target** was an overall conservation target aiming to halt the decline of biodiversity by the end of 2010.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] The world largely failed to meet the target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] It was first adopted by EU Heads of State at the EU Summit in Gothenburg, Sweden, in June 2001.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] They decided that "biodiversity decline should be halted with the aim of reaching this objective by 2010".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] One year later, the Convention on Biological Diversity's sixth Conference of the Parties adopted the Strategic Plan for the Convention in Decision VI/26.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] The World Summit on Sustainable Development held in Johannesburg in 2002 confirmed the 2010 Biodiversity Target and called for "the achievement by 2010 of a significant reduction in the current rate of loss of biological diversity".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] By the year 2006, the following nations have contributed extensively to establishment of individual Biodiversity Action Plans: Tanzania, New Zealand, Great Britain and the United States of America, called Species Recovery Plans in the USA.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] The 2004 Irish Presidency held a major stakeholder conference on the 2010 Biodiversity Target which resulted in a detailed roadmap to 2010 called the "Message from Malahide".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] At the same time, a number of organisations joined to launch the initiative Countdown2010 to support progress towards the 2010 Biodiversity Target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] On May 22, 2006 the European Commission launched its Biodiversity Communication as an implementation tool to reach the 2010 Biodiversity Target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] Subsequent Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) decisions went on to specify indicators (see: Biodiversity Indicators Partnership) for immediate testing and for possible use, and to further develop work programmes for implementation of the target.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/2010-biodiversity-target] This decision poses the question of how to measure the rate of biodiversity loss, in order to assess whether the target has been achieved by the nations who are party to the Convention.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The **Aral Sea** was an endorheic salt lake lying between Kazakhstan to its north and Uzbekistan to its south, which began shrinking in the 1960s and had largely dried up into desert by 2007.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] It was in the Aktobe and Kyzylorda regions of Kazakhstan and the Karakalpakstan autonomous region of Uzbekistan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The name roughly translates from Mongolic and Turkic languages to "Sea of Islands", a reference to the large number of islands (over 1,100) that once dotted its waters.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea drainage basin encompasses Uzbekistan and parts of Afghanistan, Iran, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Formerly the third-largest lake in the world with an area of 68,000 km2 (26,300 sq mi), the Aral Sea began shrinking in the 1960s after the rivers that fed it were diverted by Soviet irrigation projects.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] By 2007, it had declined to 10% of its original size, splitting into four lakes: the North Aral Sea, the eastern and western basins of the once far larger South Aral Sea, and the smaller intermediate Barsakelmes Lake.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] By 2009, the southeastern lake had disappeared and the southwestern lake had retreated to a thin strip at the western edge of the former southern sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In subsequent years occasional water flows have led to the southeastern lake sometimes being replenished to a small degree.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Satellite images by NASA in August 2014 revealed that for the first time in modern history the eastern basin of the Aral Sea had completely dried up.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The eastern basin is now called the Aralkum Desert.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In a Kazakhstani effort to save and replenish the North Aral Sea, the Dike Kokaral dam was completed in 2005.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As of 2013, salinity dropped, and fish were again present in sufficient numbers for some fishing to be viable.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] After the visit to Muynak in 2011, United Nations Secretary General Ban Ki-moon called the shrinking of the Aral Sea "one of the planet's worst environmental disasters".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The region's once-prosperous fishing industry has been devastated, bringing unemployment and economic hardship.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The water from the diverted Syr Darya river is used to irrigate about two million hectares (5,000,000 acres) of farmland in the Ferghana Valley.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea region is heavily polluted, with consequent serious public health problems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] UNESCO has added historical documents concerning the Aral Sea to its Memory of the World Register as a resource to study the environmental tragedy.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Amu Darya river flowed into the Caspian Sea via the Uzboy Channel until the Holocene, when its course changed to feed the Aral Sea from the south.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Geographer Nick Middleton believes it did not begin to flow into the Aral Sea until that time.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Today the Amu Darya does not reach the Aral Sea, and its mouth is in a dried-up area of what was once the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Despite its former vast size, the Aral Sea had relatively low indigenous biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] However, the Aral Sea basin had an exceptional array of endemic fish subspecies (including three endemic sturgeon species).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Most of these still survive in the North Aral Sea, but some, such as the sturgeons, have been greatly reduced or even driven to extirpation by the lake's shrinkage.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] All these fish aside from the stickleback lived an anadramous or semi-anadromous lifestyle.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] All other native fish, barring the stickleback (which persisted during the lake's shrinkage and salinity increase), were also extirpated, but many have returned to the North Aral Sea following its recovery from the 1990s onwards.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Other salt-tolerant fish species were intentionally or inadvertently introduced during the 1960s when hydropower and irrigation projects reduced the flow of fresh water thereby increasing salinity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The herring, sand smelt, and gobies were the first planktivorous fish in the lake, leading to a collapse of the lake's zooplankton population.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This in turn caused a collapse of the herring and sand smelt population from which neither species has recovered.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] All introduced species aside from the carp, snakehead, and (possibly) pipefish survived the lake's shrinkage and salinity increase, and during this time the European flounder (*Platichthys flesus*) was introduced to revive fisheries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The extirpated species (aside from possibly the pipefish) returned to the North Aral Sea following its recovery.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Herring, sand smelt, gobies and flounder persisted in the South Aral Sea until increasing salinity extirpated all but the gobies.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Prior to its shrinkage, the Aral Sea had about 250 species of native aquatic invertebrates, the majority (about 80%) being freshwater species; the rest were marine invertebrates with ties to the Ponto-Caspian and Mediterranean-Atlantic fauna.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The dominant species (excluding protozoa) were rotifers, cladocerans, and copepods.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Advanced crustaceans (Malacostraca) were represented by a single amphipod species, *Dikerogammarus aralensis*, an endemic of the Syr Darya basin.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Native gastropods included *Theodoxus pallasi* and a member of *Caspiohydrobia*.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Many of these invertebrates had their numbers drastically reduced due to the introduced fish species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Later, during an unsuccessful attempt to introduce mullet (*Mugil* sp.) to the Aral from the Caspian Sea, the rockpool shrimp (*Palaemon elegans*) was inadvertently introduced to the sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The shrimp is thought to be responsible for the extirpation of the near-endemic amphipod *Dikerogammarus aralensis*, which now survives only in the Syr Darya basin.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The copepod *Calanipeda aquaedulcis* was introduced to the Aral to replace the zooplankton species reduced by the herring population, and the North American mud crab *Rhithropanopeus harrisii* was inadvertently introduced during this attempt as well.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Later, as the lake's salinity increased, many of the freshwater-adapted species disappeared, only leaving behind the marine and saline species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] However, the zooplankton population in the North Aral Sea has recovered as salinity has decreased from the 1990s onwards, with extirpated crustacean and rotifer species returning naturally via the Syr Darya River, at the expense of the saltwater species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The cladoceran *Moina mongolica*, extirpated by the introduced fish species, has also returned.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The zebra mussel (*Dreissena polymorpha aralensis*) has been reintroduced.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In contrast, in the South Aral Sea only a few nematodes, rotifers, and parthenogenic brine shrimp (*Artemia parthenogenetica*) exist.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The future prospects for aquatic invertebrates in all remaining Aral Sea fragments depend on their future changes in salinity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Climate shifts have driven multiple phases of sea-level rise and fall.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Inflow rates from the Amu Darya and Syr Darya are affected by glacial melt rates at the rivers' headwaters as well as precipitation within the river basins; cold, dry climates restrict both processes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Geologically driven shifts in the course of the Amu Darya between the Aral Sea and the Sarykamysh basins and anthropogenic water withdrawal from Amu Darya and Syr Darya have caused fluctuations in the Aral Sea's water level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Artificial irrigation systems began in ancient times and continue to the present.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] According to Sergey Tolstov's theory, once Amu Darya was connected to Caspian sea, but this connection was broken by people 2500 years ago to feed the Aral Sea and irrigation system in Khorezm, more precisely in Khiva and other cities in this region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea was part of the western frontier of the Chinese Empire during the Tang dynasty.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] During Mongol Invasion, Mongols destroyed the cities and waterworks, which led to changes in Amu Darya's route, or some of its branches, and refilling the Lake Sarykamysh, that connected Caspian Sea again.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Aral Sea region was divided between three Mongol Hordes: the Jochi or Golden Horde, the Ilkhanids, and the Chagatai.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Muslim geographers, such as Hafiz-i Abru, wrote about the disappearance of the Aral Sea in 1417 due to diversions in both the Amu Darya and Syr Darya.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Syr Darya only resumed its natural course into the lake after 1573, when the channels that had been carved to divert its course to the south fell into disrepair.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] That caused the surface of the sea to steadily rise, flooding the basin for the next four centuries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Russian expedition of Alexey Butakov performed the first observations of the Aral Sea in 1848.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The first steamer arrived in the Aral Sea three years later.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea fishing industry began with the Russian dealers Lapshin, Ritkin, Krasilnikov, and Makeev, which later formed major fishing unions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Russian naval presence on the Aral Sea began in 1847 with the founding of Raimsk, soon renamed Fort Aralsk, near the mouth of the Syr Darya.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As the Aral Sea basin is not connected to other bodies of water, the Imperial Russian Navy deployed its vessels by disassembling them in Orenburg on the Ural River and transporting them overland to be reassembled at Aralsk.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The first two ships, assembled in 1847, were the two-masted schooners *Nikolai* and *Mikhail*.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The former was a warship; the latter a merchant vessel to establish fisheries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] They surveyed the northern part of the sea in 1848, the same year that a larger warship, the *Constantine*, was assembled.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Alexey Butakov (Алексей Бутаков), the *Constantine* completed the survey of the entire Aral Sea over the next two years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Exiled Ukrainian poet and painter Taras Shevchenko participated in the expedition and produced a number of sketches.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1851 two newly built steamers arrived from Sweden.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The geological surveys had found no coal deposits in the area so the Military Governor-General of Orenburg Vasily Perovsky ordered an "as large as possible supply" of saxaul (*Haloxylon ammodendron*) to be collected in Aralsk for the new steamers.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Saxaul wood proved not to be a suitable fuel and in the later years the Aral Flotilla was provisioned, at substantial cost, by coal from the Donbas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In the early 1960s, as part of the Soviet government plan for cotton, or "white gold", to become a major export, the Amu Darya river in the south and the Syr Darya river in the east were diverted from feeding the Aral Sea to irrigate the desert in an attempt to grow cotton, melons, rice and cereals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This plan was initially successful, and by 1988, Uzbekistan was the world's largest exporter of cotton.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] However to achieve these results farms relied heavily on agro-chemicals, including dioxins, which were used even after being banned.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Farmers, including children, were negatively affected by these chemicals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Due to abuse, the soil crucially degraded.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Though production levels declined from its peak, cotton remains Uzbekistan's main cash crop, accounting for 17% of the country's exports in 2006.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Large scale construction of irrigation canals first began in the 1930s and was greatly increased in the 1960s.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Many canals were poorly built, allowing leakage and evaporation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Between 30 and 75% of the water from the Qaraqum Canal, the largest in Central Asia, went to waste.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] It was estimated in 2012 that only 12% of Uzbekistan's irrigation canal length was waterproofed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Only 28% of interfarm irrigation channels, and 21% of onfarm channels have anti-infiltration linings, which retain on average 15% more water than unlined channels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Only 77% of farm intakes have flow gauges.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] By 1960, between 20 and 60 km3 (4.8 and 14.4 cu mi) of water each year was going to the land instead of the Aral Sea and the sea began to recede.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] From 1961 to 1970, the Aral's level fell an average of 20 cm (7.9 in) per year.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The amount of water taken for irrigation from the rivers doubled between 1960 and 2000.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In the first half of the 20th century prior to the irrigation, the sea's water level above sea level held steady at 53 m.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] By 2010, the large Aral was 27 m and the small Aral 43 m above sea level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The disappearance of the lake was no surprise to the Soviets; they expected it to happen long before.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As early as 1964, Aleksandr Asarin at the Hydroproject Institute pointed out that the lake was doomed, explaining, "It was part of the five-year plans, approved by the council of ministers and the Politburo.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Refilling of the Aral Sea was considered one of the project's main goals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] However, due to its staggering costs and the negative public opinion in Russia proper, the federal authorities had abandoned the project by 1986.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] From 1960 to 1998, the sea's surface area shrank by 60%, and its volume by 80%.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1960, the Aral Sea had been the world's fourth-largest lake with an area of 68,000 km2 (26,000 sq mi) and a volume of 1,100 km3 (260 cu mi).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Its salinity increased; having originally been 10 g/L, by 1990 it was at 376 g/L.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1987, the lake split into two separate bodies of water: the North Aral Sea (the Lesser Sea, or Small Aral Sea) and the South Aral Sea (the Greater Sea, or Large Aral Sea).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In June 1991, Uzbekistan gained independence from the Soviet Union.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Craig Murray, UK ambassador to Uzbekistan in 2002, attributes the shrinkage of the Aral Sea in the 1990s to president Islam Karimov's cotton policy.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The enormous irrigation system was massively wasteful, crop rotation was not used, and huge quantities of pesticides and fertilizer were applied.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The runoff from the fields washed these chemicals into the shrinking sea, creating severe pollution and health problems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As demand for cotton increased, the government applied more pesticides and fertilizer to the monocultured and depleted soil.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Forced labor was used and profits were siphoned off by the powerful and well-connected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 2003, the South Aral further divided into eastern and western basins.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The waters in the deepest parts of the sea were saltier and didn't mix with the top waters, so only the top of the sea was heated in the summer, resulting in faster evaporation than had been predicted.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] A plan was announced for the recovery of the North Aral Sea by building Dike Kokaral, a concrete dam separating the two halves of the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 2004, the sea's surface area was 17,160 km2 (6,630 sq mi), 25% of its original size, and a nearly fivefold increase in salinity had killed most of its flora and fauna.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Dike Kokaral was completed in 2005 and, as of 2006, some recovery of sea level had been recorded.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea is considered an example of ecosystem collapse.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The ecosystems of the Aral Sea and the river deltas feeding into it have been nearly destroyed, largely because of the salinity being dramatically higher than ocean water.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The receding sea has left huge plains covered with salt and toxic chemicals from weapons testing, industrial projects, and runoff of pesticides and fertilizer.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Because of the shrinking water source and worsening water and soil quality, pesticides were increasingly used from the 1960s to raise cotton yield, which further polluted the water with toxins (e.g.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Industrial pollution also resulted in PCB and heavy-metal contamination.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Owing to the insufficiency of water left in the Aral sea, concentrations of these pollutants rose drastically both in the remaining water and in the dry beds.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This resulted in wind-borne toxic dust that spread quite widely.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] People living in the lower parts of the river basins and former shore zones ingested pollutants through drinking local water and inhaling contaminated dust.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Furthermore, due to absorption by plants and livestock, toxins—many of which bioaccumulate and are not easily broken down or excreted by the liver and kidneys—entered the food chain.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Inhabitants of the surrounding areas commonly experience a shortage of fresh water, and health problems are widespread—including high rates of certain cancers, respiratory illnesses including tuberculosis (mostly drug resistant), digestive disorders, anaemia, and infectious diseases.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Liver, kidney, and eye problems may also be due to the toxic dust storms.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Together, this presented an unusually high fatality rate among vulnerable age groups: child mortality stood at 75 per 1,000 in 2009, while maternal mortality was 12 in every 1,000.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The dust storms have also contributed to water shortages through salt deposition.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Overusing pesticides on crops to preserve yields has exacerbated this.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Crops are destroyed where salt is deposited by the wind.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The most heavily affected fields must be flushed with water four times per day to remove salt and toxic matter.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] A 1998 study indicated that few crops (besides fodder) tolerate the degradation, restricting what Kazakhstan farmers now choose to seed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Inland seas and lakes generally moderate a region's climate through humidification, regulation of thermal energy, and peri-winter albedo effects.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Loss of water in the Aral Sea has changed surface temperatures and wind patterns.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This has led to a broader annual temperature range (about a 4 to 12 °C broadening) and more dust in storms locally and regionally.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea fishing industry, which at its peak employed some 40,000 and reportedly produced one-sixth of the Soviet Union's entire fish catch, has been devastated.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In the 1980s commercial harvests were becoming unsustainable, and by 1987 commercial harvest became nonexistent.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Due to the declining sea levels, salinity levels became too high for the 20 native fish species to survive.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The only fish that could survive the high-salinity levels was the flounder.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Also, as water has receded, former fishing towns along the original shores have become ship graveyards.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Aral, originally the main fishing port, is now about 15 kilometres from the sea and has seen its population decline dramatically since the beginning of the crisis.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The town of Moynaq in Uzbekistan had a thriving harbour and fishing industry that employed about 30,000 people; now it lies 30–90 kilometres from the shore.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Fishing boats lie scattered on the dry dusty land that was once covered by water; many have been there for 20 years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The South Aral Sea remains too saline to host any species other than halotolerant organisms.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The South Aral has been incapable of supporting fish since the late 1990s, when the flounder were killed by rising salinity levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Also destroyed is the muskrat-trapping industry in the deltas of the Amu Darya and Syr Darya, which used to yield as many as 500,000 pelts a year.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Local inhabitants are the most vulnerable population in this environmental health crisis due to the highly polluted and salinated water used for drinking and the dried seabed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Toxic chemicals associated with pesticide use have been found in blood and breast milk of mothers; specifically organochlorides, polychlorinated biphenyl compounds (PCBs), DDT compounds, and TCDD.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] These toxins can be, and often are, passed on to the children of these mothers, resulting in low birthweight and congenital abnormalities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The rate of infants being born with abnormalities is five times higher in this region than in European countries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Aral Sea region has 26% of its children born at low birthweight, which is two standard deviations away from a national population study gathered by the WHO.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Exposures to toxic chemicals from the dry seabed and polluted water have caused other health issues in women and children.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Renal tubular dysfunction has become a large health concern in children in the Aral Sea region as it is showing extremely high prevalence rates.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Renal tubular dysfunction can also be related to growth and developmental stunting.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This, in conjunction with the already high rate of low-birthweight children and children born with abnormalities, contributes to severe negative health effects and outcomes for children.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] These issues are compounded by the lack of research on maternal and child health effects caused by the demise of the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] For example, only 26 English-language peer-reviewed articles and four reports on children's health were produced between 1994 and 2008.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In addition, there is a lack of health infrastructure and resources in the Aral Sea region to combat the health issues that have arisen.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] There is a lack of medication and equipment in many medical facilities, so health professionals do not have access to the necessary supplies to do their jobs in the Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan regions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] There is also meager development of a health information system that would allow for extensive research or surveillance of emerging health issues due to Aral Sea issues.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] An absence of a primary care approach in the health systems of this region also hinders services and access that could prevent and treat issues stemming from the Aral Sea crisis, especially in women and children.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The impoverished are also particularly vulnerable to the environmental and health related effects of changes to the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] These populations were most likely to reside downstream from the Basin and in former coastal communities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] They were also among the first to be detrimentally affected, representing at least 4.4 million people in the region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Considered to have the worst health in this region, their plight was not helped when their fishery livelihoods vanished with the decreasing levels of water and loss of many aquatic species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Thus, those in poverty are entrenched in a vicious cycle.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In January 1994, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, and Kyrgyzstan signed a deal to pledge 1% of their budgets to help the sea recover.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In March 2000, UNESCO presented their "Water-related vision for the Aral Sea basin for the year 2025".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] By 2006, the World Bank's restoration projects, especially in the North Aral, were giving rise to some unexpected, tentative relief in what had been an extremely pessimistic picture.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The IFAS's work has been divided into four programs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The first phase was ineffectual for a number of reasons, but mainly because it was focused on directly improving the land around the Aral Sea, whilst not intervening in the water usage upstream.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] There was considerable concern amongst the Central Asian governments, which realised the importance of the Aral Sea in the ecosystem and the economy of Central Asia, and they were prepared to cooperate, but they found it difficult to implement the procedures of the plan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This is due in part to a lack of co-operation among the affected people.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The water flowing into the Aral Sea has long been considered an important commodity, and trade agreements have been made to supply the downstream communities with water in the spring and summer months for irrigation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In return, they supply the upstream countries with fuel during the winter, instead of storing water during the warm months for hydroelectric purposes in winter.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] However, very few legal obligations are binding these contracts, particularly on an international stage.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Phase Two of the Aral Sea Basin programme followed in 1998 and ran for five years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The main shortcomings of phase two were due to its lack of integration with the local communities involved.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The scheme was drawn up by the World Bank, government representatives, and various technical experts, without consulting those who would be affected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] An example of this was the public awareness initiatives, which were seen as propagandist attempts by people with little care or understanding of their situation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] These failures have led to the introduction of a new plan, funded by a number of institutions, including the five countries involved and the World Bank.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1997, a new plan was conceived which would continue with the previous restoration efforts of the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The main aims of this phase are to improve the irrigation systems currently in place, whilst targeting water management at a local level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The largest project in this phase is the North Aral Sea Project, a direct effort to recover the northern region of the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The North Aral Sea Project's main initiative is the construction of a dam across the Berg Strait, a deep channel which connects the North Aral Sea to the South Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Kok-Aral Dam is 13 kilometres (8 miles) long and has capacity for over 29 cubic kilometres of water to be stored in the North Aral Sea, whilst allowing excess to overflow into the South Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] On 6 October 2002, the Heads of States met again to revise the ASBP program.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The main purpose of the ASBP-2 was to set up projects that covered a vast amount of environmental, socioeconomic and water management issues.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The ASBP-2 was financed by organization such as the UNDP, World Bank, USAID, Asian Development Bank, and the governments of Switzerland, Japan, Finland, Norway and others.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Over 2 billion US Dollars was provided by the IFAS country members to the program.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] On 28 April 2009, the Heads of States came together with the Interstate commission for Water Coordination, Interstate Commission for Sustainable Development and National Experts and donors to develop the ASBP-3.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This Program was in effect from 2011- 2015.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The main purpose of the ASBP-3 was to improve the environmental and socio-economic situation of the Aral Sea Basin.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Direction One's main purpose is to propose program that focus on addressing transboundary water resources management, establishment of monitoring systems and addressing safety concerns in water facilities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Directions two's main focus is on addressing the issues related to environmental protection and improvement of the environment.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Direction three looks to address socio-economic issues by focusing on education and public health, improving unemployment rates, improving water systems, increasing sustainable development and improving living conditions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Direction Four aims to address issues related to institutional development and the development of policies and strategies that relate to sustainable development and public awareness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Funded in part by the United Nations Development Programme, implementations in Kazakhstan such as laser levelling and irrigation optimization using energy-efficient technologies has shown effectiveness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Work is being done to restore in part the North Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Irrigation works on the Syr Darya have been repaired and improved to increase its water flow, and in October 2003, the Kazakh government announced a plan to build Dike Kokaral, a concrete dam separating the two halves of the Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Work on this dam was completed in August 2005; since then, the water level of the North Aral has risen, and its salinity has decreased.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As of 2006, some recovery of sea level has been recorded, sooner than expected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The improvements to the fishing industry were largely due to the drop in the average salinity of the sea from 30 grams to 8 grams per liter; this drop in salinity prompted the return of almost 24 freshwater species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The restoration also reportedly gave rise to long-absent rain clouds and possible microclimate changes, bringing tentative hope to an agricultural sector swallowed by a regional dustbowl, and some expansion of the shrunken sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The sea, which had receded almost 100 km (62 mi) south of the port-city of Aralsk, is now a mere 25 km (16 mi) away.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Kazakh Foreign Ministry stated that "The North Aral Sea's surface increased from 2,550 square kilometers (980 sq mi) in 2003 to 3,300 square kilometers (1,300 sq mi) in 2008.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Then, it was planned to build a canal spanning the last 6 km, to reconnect the withered former port of Aralsk to the sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] On 15 June 2021 the Central Communications Service of Kazakhstan announced that they plan to plant saxaul trees on one million hectares of the drained bottom of the Aral Sea as part of efforts to stop dust storms on the region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Other efforts include expanding the sea's water level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The South Aral Sea, half of which lies in Uzbekistan, was abandoned to its fate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Most of Uzbekistan's part of the Aral Sea is completely desiccated.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Only excess water from the North Aral Sea is periodically allowed to flow into the largely dried-up South Aral Sea through a sluice in the dike.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Discussions had been held on recreating a channel between the somewhat improved North and the desiccated South, along with uncertain wetland restoration plans throughout the region, but political will is lacking.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Unlike Kazakhstan, which has partially revived its part of the Aral Sea, Uzbekistan shows no signs of abandoning the Amu Darya river to irrigate their cotton, and is moving toward oil exploration in the drying South Aral seabed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Attempts to mitigate the effects of desertification include planting vegetation in the newly exposed seabed; however, intermittent flooding of the eastern basin is likely to prove problematic for any development.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Redirecting what little flow there is from the Amu Darya to the western basin may salvage fisheries there while relieving the flooding of the eastern basin.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The reforestation is focused on plants adapted to desert conditions such as *Haloxylon ammodendron*, *Ephedra strobilacea*, *Salsola* species, and *Tamarix* species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The eventual aim is to plant up to 200,000 hectares (490,000 acres) of forest in the Uzbekistan portion.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The forest is intended to slow desertification and reduce the impact of sandstorms on nearby communities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The Interstate Commission for Water Coordination of Central Asia (ICWC) was formed on 18 February 1992 to formally unite Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan in the hopes of solving environmental, as well as socioeconomic problems in the Aral Sea region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The River Basin Organizations (the BVOs) of the Syr Darya and Amu Darya rivers were institutions called upon by the ICWC to help manage water resources.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The International Fund for Saving the Aral Sea (IFAS) was developed on 23 March 1993, by the ICWC to raise funds for the projects under Aral Sea Basin programmes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The IFAS was meant to finance programmes to save the sea and improve on environmental issues associated with the basin's drying.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] This programme has had some success with joint summits of the countries involved and finding funding from the World Bank to implement projects; however, it faces many challenges, such as enforcement and slowing progress.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Vozrozhdeniya (Russian for *rebirth*) Island is a former island of the Aral Sea or South Aral Sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Due to the ongoing shrinkage of the Aral, it became first a peninsula in mid-2001 and finally part of the mainland.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Other islands like Kokaral and Barsa-Kelmes shared a similar fate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Since the disappearance of the Southeast Aral in 2008, Vozrozhdeniya Island effectively no longer exists as a distinct geographical feature.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The area is now shared by Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1948, a top-secret Soviet bioweapons laboratory was established on the island, in the centre of the Aral Sea which is now disputed territory between Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 1971, weaponized smallpox from the island reached a nearby ship, which then allowed the virus to spread to the city of Aral.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Ten people there were infected, of whom three died, and a massive vaccination effort involving 50,000 inhabitants ensued (see Aral smallpox incident).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] The bioweapons base was abandoned in 1992 following the disintegration of the Soviet Union the previous year.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] Scientific expeditions proved this had been a site for production, testing and later dumping of pathogenic weapons.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] In 2002, through a project organized by the United States and with Uzbekistan's assistance, 10 anthrax burial sites were decontaminated.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] According to the Kazakh Scientific Center for Quarantine and Zoonotic Infections, all burial sites of anthrax were decontaminated.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] There is risk, of course, but we believe in the success of this unique project." The consortium was created in September 2005.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/aral-sea] As of 1 June 2010, 500,000 cubic meters of gas had been extracted, from 3 km down.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] A **biodiversity action plan** (**BAP**) is an internationally recognized program aimed at protecting and restoring threatened species and habitats, and at strengthening the resilience of biological systems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The concept emerged from the 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which called on participating nations to develop strategies for conserving biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] As of 2009, 191 countries had ratified the CBD, although only a portion of them had produced comprehensive BAP documents.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] A fundamental method of engagement to a BAP is thorough documentation regarding individual species, with emphasis upon the population distribution and conservation status.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] This task, while fundamental, is highly daunting, since only an estimated ten percent of the world's species are believed to have been characterized as of 2006, most of these unknowns being fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and plants.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] For many bird, mammal and reptile species, information is often available in published literature; however, for fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and many plants, such information may require considerable local data collection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] It is also useful to compile time trends of population estimates in order to understand the dynamics of population variability and vulnerability.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In some parts of the world complete species inventories are not realistic; for example, in the Madagascar dry deciduous forests, many species are completely undocumented and much of the region has never even been systematically explored by scientists.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] A species plan component of a country's BAP should ideally entail a thorough description of the range, habitat, behaviour, breeding and interaction with other species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Once a determination has been made of conservation status (e.g. rare, endangered, threatened, vulnerable), a plan can then be created to conserve and restore the species population to target levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan should also articulate which public and private agencies should implement the protection strategy and indicate budgets available to execute this strategy.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Agricultural practices can reduce the biodiversity of a region significantly.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity Action Plans for agricultural production are necessary to ensure a biodiversity friendly production.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] It has not been common for companies to integrate biodiversity aspects into their value chain, but some companies and organizations have shown overall efforts for implementing better practices.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] An existing example for guidelines on biodiversity practices in agriculture is the Biodiversity Action Plan for spice production in India.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] By planning and implementing biodiversity friendly measures, farmers can mitigate negative impacts and support positive influences.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Where a number of threatened species depend upon a specific habitat, it may be appropriate to prepare a habitat protection element of the Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Examples of such special habitats are: raised acidic bogs of Scotland; Waterberg Biosphere bushveld in South Africa; California's coastal wetlands; and Sweden's Stora Alvaret on the island of Öland.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In this case also, careful inventories of species and also the geographic extent and quality of the habitat must be documented.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Then, as with species plans, a program can be created to protect, enhance and/or restore habitat using similar strategies as discussed above under the species plans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Some examples of individual countries which have produced substantive Biodiversity Action Plans follow.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In every example the plans concentrate on plants and vertebrate animals, with very little attention to neglected groups such as fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms, even though these are also part of biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Preparation of a country BAP may cost up to 100 million pounds sterling, with annual maintenance costs roughly ten percent of the initial cost.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] If plans took into account neglected groups, the cost would be higher.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Obviously costs for countries with small geographical area or simplified ecosystems have a much lesser cost.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP has been costed in the area of several million pounds sterling.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Australia has developed a detailed and rigorous Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] This document estimates that the total number of indigenous species may be 560,000, many of which are endemic.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] A key element of the BAP is protection of the Great Barrier Reef, which is actually in a much higher state of health than most of the world's reefs, Australia having one of the highest percentages of treated wastewater.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] There are however serious ongoing concerns, particularly in regards to the ongoing negative impact on water quality from land use practices.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Also, climate change impact is feared to be significant.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Considerable analysis has been conducted on the sustainable yield of firewood production, a major threat to deforestation in most tropical countries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Biological inventory work; assessment of harvesting practices; and computer modeling of the dynamics of treefall, rot and harvest; have been carried out to adduce data on safe harvesting rates.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Extensive research has also been conducted on the relation of brush clearance to biodiversity decline and impact on water tables; for example, these effects have been analyzed in the Toolibin Lake wetlands region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] New Zealand has ratified the Convention on Biological Diversity and as part of The New Zealand Biodiversity Strategy and Biodiversity Action Plans are implemented on ten separate themes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Local government and some companies also have their own Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP recognizes impacts of large numbers of tourists to the marine and coastal diversity of the Soufrière area of the country.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The BAP specifically acknowledges that the carrying capacity for human use and water pollution discharge of sensitive reef areas was exceeded by the year 1990.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan also addresses conservation of the historic island fishing industry.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In 1992, several institutions in conjunction with native fishermen to produce a sustainable management plan for fishery resources, embodied in the Soufrière Marine Management Area.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP features significant involvement from the University of the West Indies.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Specific detailed attention is given to three species of threatened marine turtles, to a variety of vulnerable birds and a number of pelagic fishes and cetaceans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of habitat conservation the plan focusses attention on the biologically productive mangrove swamps and notes that virtually all mangrove areas had already come under national protection by 1984.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The Tanzania national BAP addresses issues related to sustainable use of Lake Manyara, an extensive freshwater lake, whose usage by humans accelerated in the period 1950 to 1990.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The designation of the Lake Manyara Biosphere Reserve under UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme in 1981 combines conservation of the lake and surrounding high value forests with sustainable use of the wetlands area and simple agriculture.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] This BAP has united principal lake users in establishing management targets.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The biosphere reserve has induced sustainable management of the wetlands, including monitoring groundwater and the chemistry of the escarpment water source.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan covers not only terrestrial species associated with lands within the UK, but also marine species and migratory birds, which spend a limited time in the UK or its offshore waters.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The UK plan encompasses "391 Species Action Plans, 45 Habitat Action Plans and 162 Local Biodiversity Action Plans with targeted actions".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] This plan is noteworthy because of its extensive detail, clarity of endangerment mechanisms, specificity of actions, follow up monitoring program and its inclusion of migrating cetaceans and pelagic birds.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] On August 28, 2007, the new Biodiversity Action Plan (BAP) [launched in 1997] identified 1,149 species and 65 habitats in the UK that needed conservation and greater protection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The updated list included the hedgehog, house sparrow, grass snake and the garden tiger moth, while otters, bottlenose dolphins and red squirrels remained in need of habitat protection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In May 2011, the European Commission adopted a new strategy to halt the loss of biodiversity and ecosystem services in the EU by 2020, in line with the commitments made at the 10th meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) held in Nagoya, Japan in 2010.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In 2012 the UK BAP was succeeded by the 'UK Post-2010 Biodiversity Framework'.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] To support the work of the UK BAP, the UK BAP website was created by JNCC in 2001.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The website contained information on the BAP process, hosted all relevant documents, and provided news and relevant updates.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In March 2011, as part of the UK government's review of websites, the UK BAP site was ‘closed’, and the core content was migrated into the JNCC website.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Content from the original UK BAP website has been archived by the National Archives as snapshots from various dates (for example, UK *BAP*: copy March 2011; copy 2012).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Twenty-six years prior to the international biodiversity convention, the United States had launched a national program to protect threatened species in the form of the 1966 Endangered Species Act.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The legislation created broad authority for analyzing and listing species of concern, and mandated that Species Recovery Plans be created.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Thus, while the USA is an unratified signer of the accord, arguably it has the longest track record and most comprehensive program of species protection of any country.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] There are about 7000 listed species (e.g. endangered or threatened), of which about half have approved Recovery Plans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] While this number of species seems high compared to other countries, the value is rather indicative of the total number of species characterized, which is extremely large.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Five major divisions of habitat have been identified in Uzbekistan’s BAP: Wetlands (including reed habitat and man-made marsh); desert ecosystems (including sandy, stony and clay); steppes; riparian ecosystems; and mountain ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Over 27,000 species have been inventoried in the country, with a high rate of endemism for fishes and reptiles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Principal threats to biodiversity are related to human activities associated with overpopulation and generally related to agricultural intensification.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Major geographic regions encompassed by the BAP include the Aral Sea Programme (threatened by long-term drainage and salination, largely for cotton production), the Nuratau Biosphere Reserve, and the Western Tien Shan Mountains Programme (in conjunction with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Some developing countries criticize the emphasis of BAPs, because these plans inherently favour consideration of wildlife protection above food and industrial production, and in some cases may represent an obstacle to population growth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The plans are costly to produce, a fact which makes it difficult for many smaller countries and poorer countries to comply.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of the plans themselves, many countries have adopted pro-forma plans including little research and even less in the way of natural resource management.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Almost universally, this has resulted in plans which emphasize plants and vertebrate animals, and which overlook fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] With regard to specific world regions, there is a notable lack of substantive participation by most of the Middle Eastern countries and much of Africa, the latter of which may be impeded by economic considerations of plan preparation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Some governments such as the European Union have diverted the purpose of a biodiversity action plan, and implemented the convention accord by a set of economic development policies with referencing certain ecosystems' protection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The definition of biodiversity under the Convention on Biological Diversity now recognises that biodiversity is a combination of ecosystem structure and function, as much as its components e.g. species, habitats and genetic resources.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity and wildlife are not the same thing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The traditional focus on threatened species in BAPs is at odds with the principles of biodiversity management because, by the time species become threatened, the processes that maintain biodiversity are already compromised.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Individual species are also regarded as generally poor indicators of biodiversity when it comes to actual planning.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] A species approach to BAPs only serves to identify and at best, apply a patch to existing problems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Increasingly, biodiversity planners are looking through the lens of ecosystem services.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Critics of biodiversity are often confusing the need to protect species (their intrinsic value) with the need to maintain ecosystem processes, which ultimately maintain human society and do not compromise economic development.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Hence, a core principle of biodiversity management, that traditional BAPs overlook, is the need to incorporate cultural, social and economic values in the process.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Modern day BAPs use an analysis of ecosystem services, key ecological process drivers, and use species as one of many indicators of change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] They would seek to maintain structure and function by addressing habitat connectivity and resilience and may look at communities of species (threatened or otherwise) as one method of monitoring outcomes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Ultimately, species are the litmus test for biodiversity – viable populations of species can only be expected to exist in relatively intact habitats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] However, the rationale behind BAPs is to "conserve and restore" biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] One of the fastest developing areas of management is biodiversity offsets.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] The principles are in keeping with ecological impact assessment, which in turn depends on good quality BAPs for evaluation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-action-plan] Contemporary principles of biodiversity management, such as those produced by the Business Biodiversity Offsets Program are now integral to any plans to manage biodiversity, including the development of BAPs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many scientists, along with the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services*, say that the main reason for biodiversity loss is a growing human population because this leads to human overpopulation and excessive consumption.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Others disagree, saying that loss of habitat is caused mainly by "the growth of commodities for export" and that population has very little to do with overall consumption.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] More important are wealth disparities between and within countries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In any case, all contemporary biodiversity loss has been attributed to human activities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Climate change is another threat to global biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, coral reefs—which are biodiversity hotspots—will be lost by the year 2100 if global warming continues at the current rate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, the change of temperatures are likely to increase fire activity driving events such as forest fires.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Still, it is the general habitat destruction (often for expansion of agriculture), not climate change, that is currently the bigger driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Invasive species and other disturbances have become more common in forests in the last several decades.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and can cause a deterioration of forest ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Groups that care about the environment have been working for many years to stop the decrease in biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Nowadays, many global policies include activities to stop biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, the UN Convention on Biological Diversity aims to prevent biodiversity loss and to conserve wilderness areas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] However, a 2020 United Nations Environment Programme report found that most of these efforts had failed to meet their goals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, of the 20 biodiversity goals laid out by the Aichi Biodiversity Targets in 2010, only six were "partially achieved" by 2020.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The current rate of global biodiversity loss is estimated to be 100 to 1000 times higher than the (naturally occurring) background extinction rate, faster than at any other time in human history, and is expected to grow in the upcoming years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The fast-growing extinction trends of various animal groups like mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish have led scientists to declare a current biodiversity crisis in both land and ocean ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2006, many more species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk that have not been formally recognized.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There is also evidence showing that species which are not formally recognized are at greater risk of extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Deforestation also plays a large role in biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] More than half of the world's biodiversity is hosted in tropical rainforest.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Regions that are subjected to exponential loss of biodiversity are referred to as biodiversity hotspots.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Since 1988 the hotspots increased from 10 to 34.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Of the total 34 hotspots currently present, 16 of them are in tropical regions (as of 2006).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Researchers have noted in 2006 that only 2.3% of the world is covered with biodiversity loss hotspots, and even though only a small percentage of the world is covered in hotspots, it host a large fraction (50%) of vascular plant species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2021, about 28 percent of the 134,400 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 37,400 species compared to 16,119 threatened species in 2006.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Research published in 2023 found that, out of 70,000 species, about 48% are facing decreasing populations due to human activities, while only 3% are seeing an increase in populations.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Biologists define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] To measure biodiversity loss rates for a particular location, scientists record the species richness and its variation over time in that area.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In ecology, local abundance is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is called relative species abundance.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There are many different biodiversity indexes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These investigate different scales and time spans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Biodiversity has various scales and subcategories (e.g. phylogenetic diversity, species diversity, genetic diversity, nucleotide diversity).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The question of *net loss* in confined regions is often a matter of debate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] An October 2020 analysis by Swiss Re found that one-fifth of all countries are at risk of ecosystem collapse as the result of anthropogenic habitat destruction and increased wildlife loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] If these losses are not reversed, a total ecosystem collapse could ensue.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, the World Wildlife Fund reported an average population decline of 68% between 1970 and 2016 for 4,400 animal species worldwide, encompassing nearly 21,000 monitored populations.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Insects are the most numerous and widespread class in the animal kingdom, accounting for up to 90% of all animal species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In the 2010s, reports emerged about the widespread decline in populations across multiple insect orders.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The reported severity shocked many observers, even though there had been earlier findings of pollinator decline.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There have also been anecdotal reports of greater insect abundance earlier in the 20th century.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many car drivers know this anecdotal evidence through the windscreen phenomenon, for example.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Causes for the decline in insect population are similar to those driving other biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] They include habitat destruction, such as intensive agriculture, the use of pesticides (particularly insecticides), introduced species, and the effects of climate change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] An additional cause that may be specific to insects is light pollution (research in that area is ongoing).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Most commonly, the declines involve reductions in abundance, though in some cases entire species are going extinct.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In some localities, there have been reports of increases in overall insect population, and some types of insects appear to be increasing in abundance across the world.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Not all insect orders are affected in the same way; most affected are bees, butterflies, moths, beetles, dragonflies and damselflies.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many of the remaining insect groups have received less research to date.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Also, comparative figures from earlier decades are often not available.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In the few major global studies, estimates of the total number of insect species at risk of extinction range between 10% and 40%, though all of these estimates have been fraught with controversy.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Scientists have studied loss of earthworms from several long-term agronomic trials.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] They found that relative biomass losses of minus 50–100% (with a mean of minus 83%) match or exceed those reported for other faunal groups.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Thus it is clear that earthworms are similarly depleted in the soils of fields used for intensive agriculture.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Earthworms play an important role in ecosystem function, helping with biological processing in soil, water, and even greenhouse gas balancing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There are five reasons for the decline of earthworm diversity: "(1) soil degradation and habitat loss, (2) climate change, (3) excessive nutrient and other forms of contamination load, (4) over-exploitation and unsustainable management of soil, and (5) invasive species".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Factors like tillage practices and intensive land use decimate the soil and plant roots that earthworms use to create their biomass.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This interferes with carbon and nitrogen cycles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Knowledge of earthworm species diversity is quite limited as not even 50% of them have been described.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Sustainable agriculture methods could help prevent earthworm diversity decline, for example reduced tillage.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The Secretariat of the Convention on Biological Diversity is trying to take action and promote the restoration and maintenance of the many diverse species of earthworms.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Since the 1980s, decreases in amphibian populations, including population decline and localized mass extinctions, have been observed in locations all over the world.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This type of biodiversity loss is known as one of the most critical threats to global biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The possible causes include habitat destruction and modification, diseases, exploitation, pollution, pesticide use, introduced species, and ultraviolet-B radiation (UV-B).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] However, many of the causes of amphibian declines are still poorly understood, and the topic is currently a subject of ongoing research.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Modeling results found that the current extinction rate of amphibians could be 211 times greater than the background extinction rate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This estimate even goes up to 25,000–45,000 times if endangered species are also included in the computation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The decline of wild mammal populations globally has been an occurrence spanning over the past 50,000 years, at the same time as the populations of humans and livestock have increased.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Nowadays, the total biomass of wild mammals on land is believed to be seven times lower than its prehistoric values, while the biomass of marine mammals had declined fivefold.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] At the same time, the biomass of humans is "an order of magnitude higher than that of all wild mammals", and the biomass of livestock mammals like pigs and cattle is even larger than that.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Even as wild mammals had declined, the growth in the numbers of humans and livestock had increased total mammal biomass fourfold.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Only 4% of that increased number are wild mammals, while livestock and humans amount to 60% and 36%.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Alongside the simultaneous halving of plant biomass, these striking declines are considered part of the prehistoric phase of the Holocene extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Since the second half of the 20th century, a range of protected areas and other wildlife conservation efforts (such as the Repopulation of wolves in Midwestern United States) have been implemented.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These have had some impact on preserving wild mammal numbers.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There is still some debate over the total extent of recent declines in wild mammals and other vertebrate species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In any case, many species are now in a worse state than decades ago.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Hundreds of species are critically endangered.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Climate change also has negative impacts on land mammal populations.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Some pesticides, like insecticides, likely play a role in reducing the populations of specific bird species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] According to a study funded by BirdLife International, 51 bird species are critically endangered and eight could be classified as extinct or in danger of extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Nearly 30% of extinction is due to hunting and trapping for the exotic pet trade.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Deforestation, caused by unsustainable logging and agriculture, could be the next extinction driver, because birds lose their habitat and their food.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] While plants are essential for human survival, they have not received the same attention as the conservation of animals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It is estimated that a third of all land plant species are at risk of extinction and 94% have yet to be evaluated in terms of their conservation status.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Plants existing at the lowest trophic level require increased conservation to reduce negative impacts at higher trophic levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, scientists warned that a third of tree species are threatened with extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This will significantly alter the world's ecosystems because their plant responses, carbon, water and nutrient cycles will be affected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Forest areas are degraded due to common factors such as logging, fire, and firewood harvesting.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Especially with forest fires and its increases, it will affect biomass recovery and affect species composition as well.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The Global Tree Assessment (GTA) has determined that "17,510 (29.9%) tree species are considered threatened with extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Possible solutions can be found in some silvicultural methods of forest management that promote tree biodiversity, such as selective logging, thinning or crop tree management, and clear cutting and coppicing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Without solutions, secondary forests recovery in species richness can take 50 years to recover the same amount as the primary forest, or 20 years to recover 80% of species richness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Human impact on the environment has driven a range of species extinct and is threatening even more today.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Multiple organizations such as IUCN and Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew suggest that around 40% of plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The majority are threatened by habitat loss, but activities such as logging of wild timber trees and collection of medicinal plants, or the introduction of non-native invasive species, also play a role.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Relatively few plant diversity assessments have considered climate change, yet it is starting to impact plants as well.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] About 3% of flowering plants are very likely to be driven extinct within a century at 2 °C (3.6 °F) of global warming, and 10% at 3.2 °C (5.8 °F).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In worst-case scenarios, half of all tree species may be driven extinct by climate change over that timeframe.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Freshwater ecosystems such as swamps, deltas, and rivers make up 1% of earth's surface.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] They are important because they are home to approximately one third of vertebrate species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Freshwater species are beginning to decline at twice the rate of species that live on land or in the ocean.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This rapid loss has already placed 27% of 29,500 species dependent on fresh water on the IUCN Red List.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Global populations of freshwater fish are collapsing due to water pollution and overfishing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Migratory fish populations have declined by 76% since 1970, and large "megafish" populations have fallen by 94% with 16 species declared extinct in 2020.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Marine biodiversity encompasses any living organism that resides in the ocean or in estuaries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] By 2018, approximately 240,000 marine species had been documented.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] But many marine species—estimates range between 178,000 and 10 million oceanic species—remain to be described.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It is therefore likely that a number of rare species (not seen for decades in the wild) have already disappeared or are on the brink of extinction, unnoticed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Human activities have a strong and detrimental influence on marine biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The main drivers of marine species extinction are habitat loss, pollution, invasive species, and overexploitation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Greater pressure is placed on marine ecosystems near coastal areas because of the human settlements in those areas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Overexploitation has resulted in the extinction of over 25 marine species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This includes seabirds, marine mammals, algae, and fish.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Examples of extinct marine species include Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) and the Caribbean monk seal (*Monachus tropicalis*).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Not all extinctions are because of humans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, in the 1930s, the eelgrass limpet (*Lottia alveus*) became extinct in the Atlantic once the *Zostera marina* seagrass population declined upon exposure to a disease.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The *Lottia alveus* were greatly impacted because the *Zostera marina* were their sole habitats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Jared Diamond describes an "Evil Quartet" of habitat destruction, overkill, introduced species and secondary extinctions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Wilson suggested the acronym HIPPO for the main causes of biodiversity loss: **H**abitat destruction, **I**nvasive species, **P**ollution, human over-**P**opulation and **O**ver-harvesting.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Habitat destruction (also termed habitat loss) occurs when a natural habitat is no longer able to support its native species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The organisms once living there have either moved elsewhere, or are dead, leading to a decrease in biodiversity and species numbers.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Habitat destruction is in fact the leading cause of biodiversity loss and species extinction worldwide.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Humans contribute to habitat destruction through the use of natural resources, agriculture, industrial production and urbanization (urban sprawl).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Other activities include mining, logging, and trawling.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Environmental factors can contribute to habitat destruction more indirectly.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Geological processes, climate change, introduction of invasive species, ecosystem nutrient depletion, water and noise pollution are some of the examples.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Loss of habitat can be preceded by an initial habitat fragmentation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Fragmentation and loss of habitat have become one of the most important topics of research in ecology as they are major threats to the survival of endangered species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, habitat loss is one of the causes in the decline of insect populations (see the section below on insects).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The direct effects of urban growth on habitat loss are well understood: building construction often results in habitat destruction and fragmentation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This leads to selection for species that are adapted to urban environments.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Small habitat patches cannot support the level of genetic or taxonomic diversity they formerly could while some more sensitive species may become locally extinct.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Species abundance populations are reduced due to the reduced fragmented area of habitat.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This causes an increase of species isolation and forces species toward edge habitats and to adapt to foraging elsewhere.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, edge effects often result in altered light, temperature, and humidity conditions that change vegetation structure and microhabitat suitability, further reducing biodiversity in fragmented urban patches.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Urban environments also favor fast-reproducing, mobile species, contributing to biotic homogenization and the global decline of ecological uniqueness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure development in Key Biodiversity Areas (KBA) is a major driver of biodiversity loss, with infrastructure present in roughly 80% of KBAs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure development leads to conversion and fragmentation of natural habitat, pollution and disturbance.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There can also be direct harm to animals through collisions with vehicles and structures.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This can have impacts beyond the infrastructure site.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, chronic noise from roads can interfere with bird song used in mating and territory defense, reducing reproductive success.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Artificial lighting can disrupt nocturnal foraging patterns, predator-prey interactions, and migratory navigation in species such as bats, amphibians, and sea turtles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Infrastructure can also create ecological traps, where animals are drawn to altered environments that ultimately reduce their fitness or survival.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Furthermore, road mortality and bird collisions with buildings and power lines cause direct harm to wildlife, with cascading impacts across trophic levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These impacts often extend well beyond the development footprint and may disrupt landscape connectivity critical for migration and climate adaptation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Fragmented landscapes also impede species' range shifts in response to climate change, making it harder for populations to track suitable environmental conditions and increasing extinction risk.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Humans are changing the uses of land in various ways, and each can lead to habitat destruction and biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The 2019 *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* found that industrial agriculture is the primary driver of biodiversity collapse.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] According to a 2005 publication, "Cultivated systems [...] cover 24% of Earth's surface".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] More than 17,000 species are at risk of losing habitat by 2050 as agriculture continues to expand to meet future food needs (as of 2020).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A global shift toward largely plant-based diets would free up land to allow for the restoration of ecosystems and biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In the 2010s over 80% of all global farmland was used to rear animals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Recent FAO data shows that livestock systems occupy about 77% of agricultural land while providing less than 20% of the global calorie supply — highlighting an imbalance between land use and nutritional output.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] As of 2022, 44% of Earth's land area required conservation attention, which may include declaring protected areas and following land-use policies.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Additionally, a 2023 analysis in *Science Advances* concluded that at least 30% of land must be actively protected and ecologically restored by 2030 to meet global biodiversity goals, aligning with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework agreed upon at COP15.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Air pollution adversely affects biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Pollutants are emitted into the atmosphere by the burning of fossil fuels and biomass, for example.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Industrial and agricultural activity releases the pollutants sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Once sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide are introduced into the atmosphere, they can react with cloud droplets (cloud condensation nuclei), raindrops, or snowflakes, forming sulfuric acid and nitric acid.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] With the interaction between water droplets and sulfuric and nitric acids, wet deposition occurs and creates acid rain.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A 2009 review studied four air pollutants (sulfur, nitrogen, ozone, and mercury) and several types of ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Air pollution affects the functioning and biodiversity of terrestrial as well as aquatic ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, "air pollution causes or contributes to acidification of lakes, eutrophication of estuaries and coastal waters, and mercury bioaccumulation in aquatic food webs".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Noise generated by traffic, ships, vehicles, and aircraft can affect the survivability of wildlife species and can reach undisturbed habitats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution is common in marine ecosystems, affecting at least 55 marine species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] One study found that as seismic noises and naval sonar increases in marine ecosystems, cetacean diversity decreases (including whales and dolphins).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Multiple studies have found that fewer fishes, such as cod, haddock, rockfish, herring, sand seal, and blue whiting, have been spotted in areas with seismic noises, with catch rates declining by 40–80%.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution has also altered avian communities and diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Noise can reduce reproductive success, minimize nesting areas, increase stress response, and reduce species abundance.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Noise pollution can alter the distribution and abundance of prey species, which can then impact predator populations.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Fossil fuel extraction and associated oil and gas pipelines have major impacts on the biodiversity of many biomes due to land conversion, habitat loss and degradation, and pollution.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] An example is the Western Amazon region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Exploitation of fossil fuels there has had significant impacts on biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] As of 2018, many of the protected areas with rich biodiversity were in areas containing unexploited fossil fuel reserves worth between $3 and $15 trillion.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The protected areas may be under threat in future.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Continued overexploitation can lead to the destruction of the resource, as it will be unable to replenish.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The term applies to natural resources such as water aquifers, grazing pastures and forests, wild medicinal plants, fish stocks and other wildlife.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A 2019 Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services report found that overfishing is the main driver of mass species extinction in oceans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Overfishing has reduced fish and marine mammal biomass by 60% since the 1800s.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It is currently pushing over one-third of sharks and rays toward extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many commercial fishes have been overharvested: a 2020 FAO report classified as overfished 34% of the fish stocks of the world's marine fisheries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] By 2020, global fish populations had declined 38% since 1970.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many regulatory measures are available for controlling overfishing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These include fishing quotas, bag limits, licensing, closed seasons, size limits, and the creation of marine reserves and other marine protected areas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The world's population numbered nearly 7.6 billion as of mid-2017 and is forecast to peak toward the end of the 21st century at 10–12 billion people.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Scholars have argued that population size and growth, along with overconsumption, are significant factors in biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Review articles, including the 2019 IPBES report, have also noted that human population growth and overconsumption are significant drivers of species decline.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A 2022 study warned that conservation efforts will continue to fail if the primary drivers of biodiversity loss continue to be ignored, including population size and growth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Other scientists have criticized the assertion that population growth is a key driver for biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] On the other hand, the correlation between a country's GDP and its footprint is strong.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The study argues that population as a metric is unhelpful and counterproductive for tackling environmental challenges.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The term *invasive* is poorly defined and often very subjective.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The European Union defines *invasive alien species* as those outside their natural distribution area that threaten biological diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Biotic invasion is considered one of the five top drivers of global biodiversity loss and is increasing because of tourism and globalization.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This may be particularly true in poorly regulated fresh water systems, though quarantines and ballast water rules have improved the situation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Invasive species may drive local native species to extinction via competitive exclusion, niche displacement, or hybridisation with related native species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Therefore, alien invasions may result in extensive changes in the structure, composition and global distribution of the biota at sites of introduction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This leads to the homogenisation of the world's fauna and flora and biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It has changed rapidly due to human activities, such as burning fossil fuels and release of methane gas and pollution.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Recent studies have found that global surface temperatures are expected to increase due to atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] But habitat destruction, e.g., for the expansion of agriculture, is currently a more significant driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A 2021 collaborative report by scientists from the IPBES and the IPCC found that biodiversity loss and climate change must be addressed simultaneously, as they are inextricably linked and have similar effects on human well-being.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2022, Frans Timmermans, Vice-President of the European Commission, said that people are less aware of the threat of biodiversity loss than they are of the threat of climate change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The interaction between climate change and invasive species is complex and not easy to assess.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Climate change is likely to favour some invasive species and harm others, but few authors have identified specific consequences of climate change for invasive species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and have negative consequences for forest ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Climate change contributes to destruction of some habitats, endangering various species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There are several plausible pathways that could lead to plant and animal species extinction from climate change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Every species has evolved to exist within a certain ecological niche, but climate change leads to changes of temperature and average weather patterns.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] These changes can push climatic conditions outside of the species' niche, and ultimately render it extinct.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Normally, species faced with changing conditions can either adapt in place through microevolution or move to another habitat with suitable conditions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] However, the speed of recent climate change is very fast.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Due to this rapid change, for example cold-blooded animals (a category which includes amphibians, reptiles and all invertebrates) may struggle to find a suitable habitat within 50 km of their current location at the end of this century (for a *mid-range scenario* of future global warming).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Climate change also increases both the frequency and intensity of extreme weather events, which can directly wipe out regional populations of species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Those species occupying coastal and low-lying island habitats can also become extinct by sea level rise.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This has already happened with Bramble Cay melomys in Australia, which was the first mammal to go extinct due to human-induced sea level rise, with the Australian government officially confirming its extinction in 2019.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Permanent global species loss (extinction) is a more dramatic phenomenon than regional changes in species composition.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] But even minor changes from a healthy stable state can have a dramatic influence on the food web and the food chain, because reductions in one species can adversely affect the entire chain (coextinction).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] This can lead to an overall reduction in biodiversity, unless alternative stable states of the ecosystem are possible.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, a study on grasslands used manipulated grassland plant diversity and found that ecosystems with higher biodiversity show more resistance of their productivity to climate extremes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] To reduce biodiversity loss related to agricultural practices, FAO encourages the use of "biodiversity-friendly management practices in crop and livestock production, forestry, fisheries and aquaculture".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The WHO has analyzed how biodiversity and human health are connected: "Biodiversity and human health, and the respective policies and activities, are interlinked in various ways.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] First, biodiversity gives rise to health benefits.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For example, the variety of species and genotypes provide nutrients and medicines." The ongoing drivers and effects of biodiversity loss has the potential to lead to future zoonotic disease outbreaks like the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Medicinal and aromatic plants are widely used in traditional medicine as well as in cosmetic and food industries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The WHO estimated in 2015 that about "60,000 species are used for their medicinal, nutritional and aromatic properties".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] There is a global trade in plants for medicinal purposes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Biodiversity contributes to the development of pharmaceuticals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] A significant proportion of medicines are derived from natural products, either directly or indirectly.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many of these natural products come from marine ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] However, unregulated and inappropriate over-harvesting (bioprospecting) could potentially lead to overexploitation, ecosystem degradation and loss of biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Users and traders harvest plants for traditional medicine either by planting them or by collecting them in the wild.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In both cases, sustainable medicinal resource management is important.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Scientists are investigating what can be done to address biodiversity loss and climate change together.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] For both of these crises, there is a need to "conserve enough nature and in the right places".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Additional measures for protecting biodiversity, beyond just environmental protection, are important.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Such measures include addressing drivers of land use change, increasing efficiency in agriculture, and reducing the need for animal agriculture.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The latter could be achieved by increasing the shares of plant-based diets.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Many governments have conserved portions of their territories under the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), a multilateral treaty signed in 1992–3.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The 20 Aichi Biodiversity Targets are part of the CBD's *Strategic Plan 2011–2020* and were published in 2010.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Aichi Target Number 11 aimed to protect 17% of terrestrial and inland water areas and 10% of coastal and marine areas by 2020 .
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Of the 20 biodiversity goals laid out by the Aichi Biodiversity Targets in 2010, only six were *partially achieved* by 2020.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The 2020 CBD report highlighted that if the status quo does not change, biodiversity will continue to decline due to "currently unsustainable patterns of production and consumption, population growth and technological developments".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The report also singled out Australia, Brazil, Cameroon and the Galapagos Islands (Ecuador) for having had one of its animals lost to extinction in the previous ten years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Following this, the leaders of 64 nations and the European Union pledged to halt environmental degradation and restore the natural world.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The pledge was not signed by leaders from some of the world's biggest polluters, namely China, India, Russia, Brazil and the United States.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Some experts contend that the United States' refusal to ratify the Convention on Biological Diversity is harming global efforts to halt the extinction crisis.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Scientists say that even if the targets for 2020 had been met, no substantial reduction of extinction rates would likely have resulted.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Others have raised concerns that the Convention on Biological Diversity does not go far enough, and argue the goal should be zero extinctions by 2050, along with cutting the impact of unsustainable food production on nature by half.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] That the targets are not legally binding has also been subject to criticism.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In December 2022, every country except the United States and the Holy See signed onto the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework at the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.This framework calls for protecting 30% of land and oceans by 2030 (30 by 30).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] It also has 22 other targets intended to reduce biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] At the time of signing the agreement, only 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The agreement includes protecting the rights of Indigenous peoples and changing the current subsidy policy to one better for biodiversity protection, but it takes a step backward in protecting species from extinction in comparison to the Aichi Targets.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Critics said the agreement does not go far enough to protect biodiversity, and that the process was rushed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] In 2019 the Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES) published the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services.* This report said that up to a million plant and animal species are facing extinction because of human activity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The IPBES is an international organization that has a similar role to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), except that it focuses on biodiversity and ecosystem services, not climate change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] The United Nations' Sustainable Development Goal 15 (SDG 15), "Life on Land", includes biodiversity targets.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Its fifth target is: "Take urgent and significant action to reduce the degradation of natural habitats, halt the loss of biodiversity and, by 2020, protect and prevent the extinction of threatened species." This target has one indicator: the Red List Index.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Nearly three-quarters of bird species, two thirds of mammals and more than half of hard corals have been recorded at World Heritage Sites, even though they cover less than 1% of the planet.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-loss] Countries with World Heritage Sites can include them in their national biodiversity strategies and action plans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The **biodiversity of New Zealand**, a large island country located in the south-western Pacific Ocean, is varied and distinctive.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The species of New Zealand accumulated over many millions of years as lineages evolved in the local circumstances.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand's pre-human biodiversity exhibited high levels of species endemism, but has experienced episodes of biological turnover.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Global extinction approximately 66 Ma (million years ago) resulted in the loss of fauna such as non-avian dinosaurs, pterosaurs and marine reptiles e.g. mosasaurs, elasmosaurs and plesiosaurs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The ancient fauna is not well known, but at least one species of terrestrial mammal existed in New Zealand around 19 Ma.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] For at least several million years before the arrival of humans, the islands had no terrestrial mammals except for bats and seals, the main component of the terrestrial fauna being insects and birds.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It was not until the 14th century CE that new species were introduced by humans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand has developed a national biodiversity action plan to address conservation of considerable numbers of threatened flora and fauna within New Zealand.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The break-up of the supercontinent of Gondwana left the resulting continents and microcontinents with shared biological affinities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Zealandia (the continental crust from which New Zealand and New Caledonia later developed) began to move away from Antarctic Gondwana 85 Ma ago, the break being complete by 66 Ma ago.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It has been moving northwards since then, changing both in relief and climate.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] About 23 million years ago New Zealand was mostly underwater.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] One estimate suggests just 18% of the present surface area remained above the water.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] However geological evidence does not rule out the possibility that it was entirely submerged, or at least restricted to small islands.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Today about 93% of the Zealandian continent remains below the sea.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Several elements of Gondwana biota are present in New Zealand today: predominantly plants, such as the podocarps and the southern beeches, but also a distinctive insect fauna, New Zealand's unusual frogs and the tuatara, as well as some of New Zealand's birds.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It seems likely that some primitive mammals also were part of the original cargo.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Whether or not any of these taxa are descendants of survivors of that ancient cargo remains unproven.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Recent molecular evidence has shown that even the iconic Gondwanan plants the southern beeches (*Nothofagus*) arrived in New Zealand after separation of Zealandia from Gondwana.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] There is a high rate of interspecific and intraspecific hybridisation in New Zealand plants and animals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The two sources of New Zealand's biodiversity following separation from Gondwana have been speciation and air- or sea-borne immigration.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Most of these immigrants have arrived from Australia, and have provided the majority of New Zealand's birds and bats as well as some plant species (carried on the wind or inside the guts of birds).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Some of these immigrants arrived long enough ago that their affinities to their Australian ancestors are uncertain; for example, the affinities of the unusual short-tailed bats (Mystacinidae) were unknown until fossils from the Miocene were found in Australia.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] *Cyanoramphus* parakeets are thought to have originated in New Caledonia and have been successful at reaching many islands in the region.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The link between the two island groups also includes affinities between skink and gecko families.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The history, climate and geology of New Zealand have created a great deal of diversity in New Zealand's vegetation types.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The main two types of forest have been dominated by podocarps and southern beech.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Podocarps (Podocarpaceae), an ancient evergreen gymnosperm family of trees, have changed little in the last 190 million years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Forests dominated by podocarps form a closed canopy with an understorey of hardwoods and shrubs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The forests of southern beeches, from the genus *Nothofagus*, comprise a less diverse habitat, with the beeches of four species dominating the canopy and allowing a single understorey.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In the north of New Zealand the podocarp forests were dominated by the ancient giant kauri.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] These trees are amongst the largest in the world, holding the record for the greatest timber volume of any tree.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The value of this was not lost on early European settlers, and most of these trees were felled.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The remaining vegetation types in New Zealand are grassland of grass and tussock, usually associated with the subalpine areas, and the low shrublands between grasslands and forests.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] These shrublands are dominated by daisies, which can become woody and 3 m high.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 7.12/10, ranking it 55th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In addition to terrestrial plants, New Zealand is home to many species of algae.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Many species of southern bull kelp are found along the coasts of the main islands, Chatham Islands and the Subantarctic Islands.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Until 2006, it was thought that no mammals, other than bats and marine mammals, had reached New Zealand before humans did.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The discovery of a femur and mandibles of an extinct non-volant (non-flying) mammal in Otago, dated at 16–19 million years old, has changed the view of New Zealand's evolutionary history, as it strongly suggests that mammals had been part of New Zealand's fauna since the break-up of Gondwana.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It is not known when, or why, land mammals became extinct in New Zealand but there were none present on New Zealand for several million years before the arrival of humans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The short-tailed bats (from the monotypic family Mystacinidae), first arrived in the Oligocene or before.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Some plants have evolved with the bats and are fertilised on the ground by the bats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The long-tailed bat (*Chalinolobus tuberculatus*), a more recent arrival, is relatively common.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The Miocene St Bathans fauna also preserves remains of a vesper bat and several *incertae sedis* species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Birds comprise the most important part of New Zealand's vertebrate fauna.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It is uncertain if many birds in New Zealand are descended from Gondwanan stock, as DNA evidence suggests that even the ratites (the kiwis and the moas) arrived after the split from Antarctica.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Recent studies suggest that New Zealand wrens are Gondwanan descendants.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] DNA studies seem to indicate that the wrens are the most ancient of all passerines, splitting from the ancestral passerine stock at the time New Zealand become an isolated land mass.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In the absence of mammals, birds diversified into the niches usually filled by mammals in other ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The moas, of which there were eleven species, were large browsers, and were in turn the prey species of the giant Haast's eagle.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Both the moas and the eagle became extinct shortly after the arrival of humans in New Zealand sometime around 1300 CE.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It appears that human hunters exterminated the moa populations, which deprived the Haast's eagle of its primary food source, leading to the extinction of that species as well.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand's emblematic kiwis fill the role of small foragers of the leaf-litter, and the enigmatic adzebill was a universal omnivore.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The wattlebirds, Callaeidae, are a family endemic to New Zealand, but many other New Zealand birds show clear affinities to Australia, including the New Zealand pigeon and the New Zealand falcon, as well as various parrots, rails, waders, owls, and seabirds (albeit often with a New Zealand twist).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Of the 245 species of birds from the greater New Zealand (the main islands along with the offshore islands, also including Norfolk Island), 174 were endemic, roughly 71%.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Of these, about 32% of the genera were endemic.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] No agamas or iguanas are recorded from New Zealand; lizards are represented by geckos and skinks, which arrived multiple times.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The fossil record shows a highly diverse herpetofauna during the Miocene, with a mekosuchine crocodile and meiolaniid and pleurodire turtles being known from the St Bathans fauna.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The tuatara, reaching 60 cm (23.6 inches), is New Zealand's largest living reptile, a last remnant from the once diverse clade that was Sphenodontia.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Frogs, which because of their intolerance for saltwater are assumed to have descended from ancestors that broke off from Gondwana, are one of the few exceptions to the rule that amphibians are never found on oceanic islands (another being the frogs of Fiji).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand's few wholly freshwater fishes are derived from diadromous species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand's terrestrial invertebrate community displays strong Gondwanan affinities, and has also diversified strongly, if unevenly.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] There are over a thousand species of snail, and many species of insect have become large and in many cases flightless, especially grasshoppers and beetles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] There are, however, fewer than 12 species of ant.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The most famous of New Zealand's insects, the wētā, are ground-living relatives of the crickets that often reach enormous proportions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Many endemic marine invertebrate species, particularly marine snails, have evolved in the seas surrounding New Zealand.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Of an estimated 20,000 species of New Zealand fungi, only about 4,500 are known.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] New Zealand also has two subspecies of endemic cetaceans, Hector's dolphin and its close relative Maui's dolphin.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The arrival of humans has impacted the natural environment, posing a threat to native species and resulting in the extinction of several.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] This is predominantly because many species in New Zealand have evolved in the absence of mammalian predators for the last few million years (a situation known as ecological naivety), thus losing the responses needed to deal with such threats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The date of arrival of the first human settlers (the antecedents of the Māori) in New Zealand is given as around 1300 CE, and evidence suggests that Polynesian rats seemed to have arrived at a similar date.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Their arrival set off a first wave of extinctions, eliminating smaller defenceless ground nesting birds such as the New Zealand owlet-nightjar.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] A second wave of extinctions was triggered by the arrival of the Māori, who hunted many of the larger species, such as the moa, adzebill and several large ducks and geese, for food.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The Haast's eagle and Eyles's harrier are thought to have gone extinct due to the loss of their food source.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] A third wave of extinction began with the arrival of European settlers, who brought with them numerous new mammal species, particularly the predatory domestic cat, and initiated more habitat modification.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In all, over 50% of New Zealand's bird species are considered extinct, along with a species of bat (the New Zealand greater short-tailed bat), several frogs (only four frog types remain), a freshwater fish (the New Zealand greyling), skinks, and geckos.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In some instances, the extinction of New Zealand's native fauna has brought about a natural colonisation from Australia.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In the case of the silvereye, which colonised New Zealand in the 19th century, it had no relative in New Zealand's original fauna and is now restricted to newer man-made niches.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] In the case of the black swan (which was originally thought to have been introduced by humans but is now suspected to have self-introduced), the invading species re-occupied part of its former range (the extinct New Zealand swan is now believed to be a subspecies of the black swan).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The arrival of the pūkeko and the swamp harrier is more interesting, mirroring the arrival of related species in the past, before they evolved into the takahē and the Eyles's harrier.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Once these specialised birds declined and (in the case of the harrier) became extinct, their niches were available and colonisation could occur again.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The New Zealand government, through the Department of Conservation, works aggressively to protect what remains of New Zealand's biological heritage.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] It has pioneered work on island restoration where offshore islands are systematically cleared of introduced species such as goats, feral cats and rats.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] This then allows the re-introduction of native species that can hopefully flourish in the absence of non-native predators and competitors.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] The longest running project of this type is on Cuvier Island, but other islands are also being used such as Tiritiri Matangi and Mangere Island.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-of-new-zealand] Establishment of conservation areas is not restricted to islands however and several ecological islands have been established on the New Zealand mainland which are isolated by the use of pest-exclusion fences.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:biodiversity-action-plan/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
